elonging, migration and diasporas, the carceral state, renegotiating relationships with land, ancestral knowledge as radical futurity, and shifting paradigms of inequity. Foregrounding the powerful resilience of communities of color, FUTURE/PRESENT advances the role of artists as first responders to injustices, creative stewards in the cohesion and health of communities, and innovative strategists for equity.Selected contributors. Dahlak Brathwaite, adrienne maree brown, Jeff Chang, Tameca Cole, Ofelia Esparza, Antoine Hunter, Nobuko Miyamoto, Wendy Red Star, Spel, Jose Antonio Vargas, Carrie Mae Weems, Hinaleimoana Kwai Kong Wong-Kalu  afunded by ArtChangeUS  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnti-racismzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aArts and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aArtsxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aRacial justicezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aRacism and the artszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAkootchook Warden, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlapaʻi, Kapena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlcazar, Daniel Andres, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Devin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarez, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarez, Daniela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlvarez, Maribel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnthony, Nāʻālehu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/